Looking at the board:

- Top row: `X | 1 | O` (only [1] open)
- Middle row: `3 | O | 5` ([3] and [5] both open, but O already in 4 prevents three-in-a-row)
- Bottom row: `X | 7 | O` (only [7] open)

Take [1] to threaten a double attack:

- `X X O` top-row win for me.
- Also gives me a fork on the diagonal X–O–O (no longer usable), but more importantly it blocks any O threat on the top row and leaves Player 0 without an immediate blocking move for my next set-up.
